My wife, who has a genuine phobia of needles, got her wisdom teeth out yesterday. It marked the end of a long journey of tears and anxiety.

Although we trusted that the surgeon, anaesthetist and nurses had the expertise, their ability to communicate was what stood out most.

1/2

@malcoad Absolutely not. In my opinion, it's a critical part of their knowledge and expertise. It was as though, through their initial interactions, they were quickly assessing her anxiety levels and adjusting their manner accordingly - it was fascinating to watch. 1/2

THREAD: Content note: mental health 

Today I went to get my mental health plan from my local clinic at the only bulk billing centre I've found close to my house. I thought it would be another run of the mill 10 minute appointment and 1/

2/ I'd collect my paperwork to continue receiving mental health care under Medicare - a right that all of us have. 

I was stonewalled upon arrival, told that the new GP I came in to see today didn't like to do plans for people he didn't know.

7/I asked him how preventing me from accessing a mental health care plan would be helpful to my mental health. He kept insisting I come back and see the other doctor.

I asked him where in the Mental Health Act it outlines that he can deny me this plan that I am asking for.

8/Eventually he relented. He said that mental health isn't his area of 'interest' and if he does one plan he'll have to do all of them. When I told him this was his job and it's not my concern whether my mental health is interesting to him or not he shut the conversation down.

9/He wouldn't look at me as I left.  I told him to think about how this makes people with mental health issues feel as I walked out with my mental health care plan.

I'm lucky my first GP was kind and  she understood the basics of public health, and her responsibilities as a GP.

11/I've lodged a complaint with AHPRA, let's see what happens. Obviously this is a structural problem that ultimately comes down to the fact that GPs are gatekeepers for bulk billed mental health. 

I don't really like to share personal things online much, but I wanted ensure

12/ others out there know their rights. So that people aren't made to feel ashamed for seeking out mental help. If you aren't on a mental health care plan, I can guarantee you that your friends or family members are. No one should be treated this way for trying to get healthcare.

“...into decreased or increased levels of suicide.” 

We are being sold an idea to prevent Indig suicide that has significant failings and lacks crucial evidence.

The link again for “A critical analysis of myth-perpetuating research on suicide prevention” https://t.co/5rqe2VzbEG https://t.co/NbNc5GQC98

Also, suicide doesn’t discriminate. It’s human behaviour with many contexts in which it can happen and be viewed. In preventing what I call post-contact Indigenous suicidal behaviour, it can’t be simply looked at it through a cultural lens. The risks factors aren’t cultural.

I use the term post-contact as we do not know the context for suicide or how it was even defined or viewed prior to white settlement. The absence of a word for suicide in language is *not* evidence of the absence of suicide and/or suicidal behaviour. I’ll discuss this more later.

In Indigenous suicide prevention if we define culture as, living on country, speaking language, engaging in ceremony, living our own people’s custom and practicing lore, these elements are only of value in prevention if the suicidal person expresses as much or assessed as needed.

Last time I hosted this account I wrote about how I did not believe culture to be the mechanism to bring down suicide in areas where culture (as defined above) was not absent. Highest rates of Indig suicides are in areas where these culture elements exist and are practiced daily.

But what we continue to see is Indig suicide prevention programs based on these elements as if there must be a deficit. Let me be clear. These elements may be of use in suicide prevention, if they have been identified (via assessment) as having any use to the individual.

I’ll discuss assessment later + discuss the docs that seem to guide Indig suicide prevention + direct where the funding goes. These docs make up a concordance of literature in Indig suicide prevention & are mostly co/authored by the same people who receive the 💰. Coincidence 🤔

@VirtueVirus_ I had the worst kind of anxiety attacks once and the best thing you could do is 1: get prescription medication for it but only take a few so u know it works THEN keep it around so you KNOW it’s there in case you really feel you need it. It’s there for peace of mind...

@VirtueVirus_ Which can disempower anxiety. 2nd is.. get up and go for a 25 minute walk everyday. Do not depend on medication... you CAN manage anxiety, try use it as a tool.  I would walk multiple times everyday listening to lighthearted podcasts or music(this gets you out of your own head.)

@VirtueVirus_ 3rd - pay attention to what you’re putting in your body. Sugar and caffeine will send your anxiety sky high, at stressful times consume blueberries.. camomile tea. Avacados. Bananas etc. all these lower cortisol. Your stomach is the 2nd brain https://t.co/pGBdjDjDHW
